n Chandi, \n&gt;&gt;&gt;of &gt;&gt;&gt;which the navarna we know of, is probably the mildest. T=\r\no chant &gt;&gt;&gt;one of \n&gt;&gt;&gt;these mantras and awaken the same needs initiation. T=\r\nhis, &gt;&gt;&gt;they said, is a \n&gt;&gt;&gt;part of the &gt;&gt;&gt;entire Chandi sadhana. What is y=\r\nour &gt;&gt;opinion on this?&gt;&gt;&gt;\n\nBroadly speaking most of the above is true from =\r\nthe traditional *Sakta* \nperspective. Sri Sri Chandi sadhana as enjoined by=\r\n Kalikula emphasises MANTRA \nsadhana. Merely chanting the Devi Mahatmyam te=\r\nxt is not the same as Sri Sri \nChandi sadhana, as per this view. It has var=\r\nious mantric nuances and practices \nincluding other mantras and bijas and w=\r\nays to make them work. I will expand on \nthis at the end of this post after=\r\n addressing your other points.\n\n&gt;&gt;&gt;As a corollary to your above paragraph, =\r\none can therefore read the &gt;&gt;&gt;text of \n&gt;&gt;&gt;the Chandi in a pouranik approach=\r\n, as a sacred myth? There &gt;&gt;&gt;are people, \n&gt;&gt;&gt;specially in Bengal, who do a =\r\nChandipath on their own &gt;&gt;&gt;without having \n&gt;&gt;&gt;undergone any formal initiati=\r\non. How good or bad is &gt;&gt;&gt;this practise?\n\nAs always there will be varied be=\r\nliefs and opinions ranging from the very rigid \ntraditional extreme to the =\r\nvery liberal and casual new-age extreme based on \none&#39;s personal affiliatio=\r\nns, family and cultural influences. I will speak for \n*myself*. I prefer th=\r\ne moderate view that is respectful to tradition but does \nnot allow traditi=\r\non to be one more fetter. \n\n\nQuite often many of our beliefs are fear-based=\r\n rather than knowledge-based. \nHowever undigested, unassimilated and unharm=\r\nonised information gathered from the \ninternet or even the print media is n=\r\not knowledge. There is no need to be \nfearful as long as one is not experim=\r\nenting with mantramarga based on fragmented \ninformation gathered from book=\r\ns or worse still the internet. As long as one does \nthe parayana along with=\r\n other supportive practices such as kirtan, swadhyaya, \nreflection and bhak=\r\nti bhava, initiation need not be a binding factor. However if \none wishes t=\r\no do Sri Sri Chandi sadhana in a full-fledged manner as per the \ntraditiona=\r\nl Sakta perspective, better be initiated. If one strongly wills it \n(sankal=\r\npa) and is suited to it, the external guru and initiation will happen on \nt=\r\nheir own accord. For the rest who are not predominantly suited to or inclin=\r\ned \ntowards mantramarga, this discussion is not relevant. \n\n\n&gt;&gt;&gt;There &gt;&gt;&gt;ar=\r\ne people, specially in Bengal, who do a Chandipath on &gt;&gt;&gt;their own \n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;w=\r\nithout having undergone any formal initiation. How &gt;&gt;&gt;good or bad is &gt;&gt;&gt;thi=\r\ns \n&gt;&gt;&gt;practise?\n\nBengal is one of the areas of the subcontinent where Kalik=\r\nula flourished in a \nfull-fledged manner at one time. So at the collective =\r\nlevel Kalikula is deeply \nembedded in the collective unconscious and thereb=\r\ny the tendency to do Chandipath \nirrespective of initiation. To undertand t=\r\nhis one needs to appreciate the \ndynamics between Kundalini and *KULA* KUND=\r\nALINII which are akin to the \nindividual unconscious and collective unconsc=\r\nious. If a particular \nfamily/significant member of the family has practice=\r\nd the sadhana of a devata \nfor sometime, the descendants automatically have=\r\n its influence in their \nunconscious. That is why we are advised to worship=\r\n the kuladevata along with \nishta devata though ishta devata remains a majo=\r\nr focus. The same applies to \nparayana too. Bengal was at one time a hotbed=\r\n for the living and breathing \ntradition of Kalikula. Though we do not see =\r\nits flowering at the same level or \nin the same form today, at the unseen a=\r\nnd unconscious collective level, the \nage-old Kalikula is very much alive a=\r\nnd breathing. \n\n\nSpiritual life is all about Awareness and oversimplifying =\r\nit further, making the \nunconscious conscious is what Awareness is about. I=\r\nn true Advaitic fashion the \ncollective and individual consciousness are no=\r\nt separate. The advent of Sri \nRamakrishna is a predictable culmination of =\r\nthe flowering of Kalikula at a \ncollective level. His advent marks a major =\r\nmilestone in not just Kalikula \nsadhana but Sakta sadhana itself. Irrespect=\r\nive of the physical death of Sri \nRamakrishna, his satsangha is possible fo=\r\nr all sincere seekers. Whilst swadhyaya \nof the Kathamrta is the easiest wa=\r\ny to revel in his Satsangha, it is possible to \nconnect with him through a =\r\ncombination of trust (sraddha) and sense of \nbelongingness too. If you cons=\r\nider him as your APTA, he automatically becomes \nyour apta at a manasik lev=\r\nel. This sense of belongingness straightaway opens the \ndoors of your heart=\r\n and makes his grace and protection possible. \n\n\nIn view of the above discu=\r\nssed factors, it might be okay to do Chandi parayana \nwithout initiation, i=\r\nn our times. Initiation could happen in the long run if it \nis meant to be.=\r\n However traditionally speaking Sri Sri Chandipath without \ninitiation is u=\r\nnimaginable as Sri Sri Chandi&#39;s integrated sadhana includes \nvarious other =\r\nmantras and bijas that are generally not written in texts though \nsome text=\r\ns talk about them without giving the complete details. Diksha includes \nall=\r\n this and much more. Here a word on `diksha&#39; itself is in order to clarify =\r\n\nthe difference between uninitiated Devi Mahatmya parayana and initiated Sr=\r\ni Sri \nChandi sadhana. \n\n\nDiksha differs in accordance with the sampradaya =\r\nor the lineage within Kalikula \nor Srikula. To understand `diksha&#39; itself, =\r\none needs to examine certain \ndifferences (bhedas), of which the following =\r\nare most important:\n\n1. Guru Parampara: This forms the core of Devi Upasana=\r\n and the other bhedas \n(differences) are in a way based on this.\n\n2. Sampra=\r\ndaya: Guru of any authentic lineage should necessarily belong to one of \nth=\r\ne recognized sampradayas. \n\n\n3. Diksha: Depending on the disciple&#39;s eligibi=\r\nlity and the Guru&#39;s capability, \nthe type of diksha too varies. \n\n\n4. Yaga =\r\nBheda: There are four levels of Yajna or yaga - Antaryaga, \nBahiryaga,Mahay=\r\naga and Rahoyaga. Guru initiates the disciple into one or more of \nthese pa=\r\nths depending on the adhikara (aptitudes, needs and capabilities) of the \ns=\r\nadhaka. Only antaryaga and bahiryaga are relevant to our discussion. I have=\r\n \nalready expanded on this in another post on Yajna. \n\n\n5. Devata Bheda: Th=\r\nough the Devi is only One, depending on the samskara and \nvasana of the ini=\r\ntiate, he is initiated into the worship of Kali or Sri and thus \nthe paths =\r\nof Kalikula and Srikula or Kalividya and Srividya. \n\n\n6. Achara Bheda: Depe=\r\nnding on the initiate&#39;s samskara and adhikara, broadly \nspeaking there are =\r\nseven acharas- Vedachara, Vaisnavachara, Saivachara, \nDakshinachara, Vamach=\r\nara, Siddhantachara , and Kaulachara. Within the framework \nof Sakta sadhan=\r\na, there are only three acharas- Samaya, Dakshina and Kaulachara. \nIt is hi=\r\nghly misleading to speak of the *superiority* of one achara over the \nother=\r\n. The path, the chosen form of the Mother (Kali or Sri), the means of \nwors=\r\nhip, are all differently devised to suit the varying temperaments of the \np=\r\nractitioners. All forms of the Devi and all paths of sadhana are equally \nr=\r\nespectable and ancient enough. The differences pertain more to the practiti=\r\noner \nand NOT TO THE DIVINITY. As such we are advised not to degrade or cri=\r\nticize any \npath or deity. All upasanas lead to the Devi and all sadhakas h=\r\nave the Devi \nwithin them. To talk lowly of any other sadhana marga or rupa=\r\n of the Devi \namounts to insulting the Devi Herself. As Sri Bhaskararaya ob=\r\nserves with \ncharacteristic tolerance, &quot;all vidyas are not different, a com=\r\nparison of one to \nanother (in the texts) is merely for the sake of praisin=\r\ng and encouraging its \nperformance&quot;. One could as well extend this toleranc=\r\ne (if not acceptance) to all \nforms of God and all paths of attaining Her/H=\r\nim. In the ultimate reckoning, any \ndivision is relative as there is only t=\r\nhe ONE. Advaita is the true essence of \nSakta sadhana. All paths are practi=\r\ncally along a *circular* continuum. An \nintellectual debate on the differen=\r\nces between various paths is irrelevant to \nsadhana itself though it has re=\r\nlevance to academicians or to the respective \nworld-view of the sadhaka. In=\r\nstead sadhakas should focus on the underlying unity \nof all paths and the u=\r\nltimate Oneness of all forms of the Divine. This is a \nmajor tenet of Sakta=\r\n sadhana.\n\n7. Mantra Bheda =E2=80=93 Based on certain factors including the=\r\n sadhaka&#39;s adhikara \nbheda, he is initiated into a different mantra. It is =\r\nnot uncommon that the same \nsadhaka is initiated into various forms of the =\r\nmantra progressively in a gradual \nmanner if he persists with commitment. F=\r\nor instance in Sri Vidya upasana the \nmantra of Sri has five variant versio=\r\nns- Bala, Panchadashi, Shodashi, Para \nshodashi and Guhya shodashi. Bala ma=\r\nntra is the entry level or preparatory level \nmantra for Sri Vidya. Likewis=\r\ne the navakshari or navarna mantra too has SEVEN \nVARIANT versions, of whic=\r\nh the Navarna mantra that most written texts include is \nthe mildest and ak=\r\nin to the entry level Bala mantra in Sri Vidya upasana. \n\n\nThe *details* of=\r\n the seven variant versions of the navakshari or the twelve \ndifferent ways=\r\n of doing Sri Sri Chandi path are really unnecessary to our \ncurrent discus=\r\nsion. Instead in my next post I will write more on MANTRA and its \ncentral =\r\nimportance in sadhana as per the Sakta world-view. \n\n\nFinally a word on `Va=\r\nk and `artha&#39; too is in order here. It is true that one \nderives great bene=\r\nfit by chanting a mantra in its original form. No doubt \ntranslation of a m=\r\nantra is NOT the same as the mantra in its original form as \n`vak&#39;. Undoubt=\r\nedly `Sabda&#39; comes first and then only the `artha&#39; follows (&quot;Artha \nSrishta=\r\neh Purvam Sabda srushtih&quot;). However one has to bear in mind that `Vak&#39; \nand=\r\n `Artha&#39; are interdependent and inseparable. I will elaborate on \nSabda/Vak=\r\n/Artha in my next post along with Sri Bhaskararaya makhin&#39;s commentary \nand=\r\n the importance accorded to the fifteen levels of meaning (artha) of a \nman=\r\ntra, so much so that he even affirms that, &quot;the mere utterance of sabda \nwi=\r\nthout a knowledge of the true import bears no fruit, even as the offering \n=\r\nthrown over ashes in the absence of fire does not burst into flame&quot;. I will=\r\n \nexamine both sides of `sabda&#39; and `artha&#39; in my next post as and when I c=\r\nan. All \nIndian traditions that explore `Vak&#39; or `Sabda&#39; agree that both ar=\r\ne inseparable. \nThe very mention of the words `sabda&#39; and `artha&#39; brings to=\r\n my mind the most \nbeautiful mangala sloka from Kalidasa&#39;s `Raghuvamsa&#39; whe=\r\nrein he compares the \ninseparable and interdependent nature of `Vak&#39; and `A=\r\nrtha&#39; to `Siva&#39; and `Sakti&#39; \nthe parents of the entire universe =E2=80=A6.\n=\r\n\nvagarthaviva samprkthau vagarthaaprathipaththaye / \njagathaha pitharau van=\r\ndhe parvathiparameshvarau // \n\nRegards,\nSatya Prakash\n\n--- In vedic-wisdom@=\r\nyahoogroups.com, rajarshi nandy &lt;rajarshi14@...&gt; wrote:\n&gt;\n&gt; Dear Satya Prak=\r\nash ji,\n&gt; \n&gt; Thank you for your beautiful=C3=82=C2=A0analysis of Sri Sri Ch=\r\na