atever is suited to you will happ=\r\nen in the natural flow of Life. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;In this post I will also touch upon=\r\n certain other topics raised in some related posts while primarily addressi=\r\nng Rajarshi ji&#39;s queries.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;I had talked to a few people w=\r\nho adhere to different paramparas &gt;&gt;&gt;within the broader subset of =\r\nKalikula. They said that the &gt;&gt;&gt;initiation in Chandi sadhana in re=\r\nquired for not only the parayana &gt;&gt;&gt;but also (mostly?) because of\n=\r\n the main mantra. Normally we are &gt;&gt;&gt;accustomed with only the nava=\r\nrna mantra, but there are various &gt;&gt;&gt;other mantras of the differen=\r\nt aspects of the Universal Chandi, of &gt;&gt;&gt;which the navarna we know=\r\n of, is probably the mildest. To chant &gt;&gt;&gt;one of these mantras and=\r\n awaken the same needs initiation. This, &gt;&gt;&gt;they said, is a part o=\r\nf the &gt;&gt;&gt;entire Chandi sadhana. What is your &gt;&gt;opinion on th=\r\nis?&gt;&gt;&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Broadly speaking most of the above is true from the =\r\ntraditional *Sakta* perspective. Sri Sri Chandi sadhana as enjoined by Kali=\r\nkula emphasises MANTRA sadhana. Merely chanting the Devi Mahatmyam text is =\r\nnot the same as Sri Sri Chandi sadhana, as per this view. It has various ma=\r\nntric nuances and practices including other mantras and bijas and ways to m=\r\nake them work. I will expand on this at the end of this post after addressi=\r\nng your other points.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;As a corollary to your\n above para=\r\ngraph, one can therefore read the &gt;&gt;&gt;text of the Chandi in a poura=\r\nnik approach, as a sacred myth? There &gt;&gt;&gt;are people, specially in =\r\nBengal, who do a Chandipath on their own &gt;&gt;&gt;without having undergo=\r\nne any formal initiation. How good or bad is &gt;&gt;&gt;this practise?&lt;BR&gt;=\r\n&lt;BR&gt;As always there will be varied beliefs and opinions ranging from the ve=\r\nry rigid traditional extreme to the very liberal and casual new-age extreme=\r\n based on one&#39;s personal affiliations, family and cultural influences. I wi=\r\nll speak for *myself*. I prefer the moderate view that is respectful to tra=\r\ndition but does not allow tradition to be one more fetter. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Quite of=\r\nten many of our beliefs are fear-based rather than knowledge-based. However=\r\n undigested, unassimilated and unharmonised information gathered from the i=\r\nnternet or even the print media is not knowledge. There is no need to be fe=\r\narful as long as one is not experimenting with\n mantramarga based on fragme=\r\nnted information gathered from books or worse still the internet. As long a=\r\ns one does the parayana along with other supportive practices such as kirta=\r\nn, swadhyaya, reflection and bhakti bhava, initiation need not be a binding=\r\n factor. However if one wishes to do Sri Sri Chandi sadhana in a full-fledg=\r\ned manner as per the traditional Sakta perspective, better be initiated. If=\r\n one strongly wills it (sankalpa) and is suited to it, the external guru an=\r\nd initiation will happen on their own accord. For the rest who are not pred=\r\nominantly suited to or inclined towards mantramarga, this discussion is not=\r\n relevant. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;There &gt;&gt;&gt;are people, specially in B=\r\nengal, who do a Chandipath on &gt;&gt;&gt;their own &gt;&gt;&gt;without hav=\r\ning undergone any formal initiation. How &gt;&gt;&gt;good or bad is &gt;&gt=\r\n;&gt;this practise?&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Bengal is one of the areas of the subcontinent w=\r\nhere Kalikula flourished in a\n full-fledged manner at one time. So at the c=\r\nollective level Kalikula is deeply embedded in the collective unconscious a=\r\nnd thereby the tendency to do Chandipath irrespective of initiation. To und=\r\nertand this one needs to appreciate the dynamics between Kundalini and *KUL=\r\nA* KUNDALINII which are akin to the individual unconscious and collective u=\r\nnconscious. If a particular family/significant member of the family has pra=\r\ncticed the sadhana of a devata for sometime, the descendants automatically =\r\nhave its influence in their unconscious. That is why we are advised to wors=\r\nhip the kuladevata along with ishta devata though ishta devata remains a ma=\r\njor focus. The same applies to parayana too. Bengal was at one time a hotbe=\r\nd for the living and breathing tradition of Kalikula. Though we do not see =\r\nits flowering at the same level or in the same form today, at the unseen an=\r\nd unconscious collective level, the age-old Kalikula is very much alive and=\r\n breathing.\n &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Spiritual life is all about Awareness and oversimplify=\r\ning it further, making the unconscious conscious is what Awareness is about=\r\n. In true Advaitic fashion the collective and individual consciousness are =\r\nnot separate. The advent of Sri Ramakrishna is a predictable culmination of=\r\n the flowering of Kalikula at a collective level. His advent marks a major =\r\nmilestone in not just Kalikula sadhana but Sakta sadhana itself. Irrespecti=\r\nve of the physical death of Sri Ramakrishna, his satsangha is possible for =\r\nall sincere seekers. Whilst swadhyaya of the Kathamrta is the easiest way t=\r\no revel in his Satsangha, it is possible to connect with him through a comb=\r\nination of trust (sraddha) and sense of belongingness too. If you consider =\r\nhim as your APTA, he automatically becomes your apta at a manasik level. Th=\r\nis sense of belongingness straightaway opens the doors of your heart and ma=\r\nkes his grace and protection possible. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;In view of the above discuss=\r\ned\n factors, it might be okay to do Chandi parayana without initiation, in =\r\nour times. Initiation could happen in the long run if it is meant to be. Ho=\r\nwever traditionally speaking Sri Sri Chandipath without initiation is unima=\r\nginable as Sri Sri Chandi&#39;s integrated sadhana includes various other mantr=\r\nas and bijas that are generally not written in texts though some texts talk=\r\n about them without giving the complete details. Diksha includes all this a=\r\nnd much more. Here a word on `diksha&#39; itself is in order to clarify the dif=\r\nference between uninitiated Devi Mahatmya parayana and initiated Sri Sri Ch=\r\nandi sadhana. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Diksha differs in accordance with the sampradaya or t=\r\nhe lineage within Kalikula or Srikula. To understand `diksha&#39; itself, one n=\r\needs to examine certain differences (bhedas), of which the following are mo=\r\nst important:&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;1. Guru Parampara: This forms the core of Devi Upasana=\r\n and the other bhedas (differences) are in a way based on\n this.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;2. =\r\nSampradaya: Guru of any authentic lineage should necessarily belong to one =\r\nof the recognized sampradayas. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;3. Diksha: Depending on the disciple=\r\n&#39;s eligibility and the Guru&#39;s capability, the type of diksha too varies. &lt;B=\r\nR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;4. Yaga Bheda: There are four levels of Yajna or yaga - Antaryaga, Ba=\r\nhiryaga,Mahayaga and Rahoyaga. Guru initiates the disciple into one or more=\r\n of these paths depending on the adhikara (aptitudes, needs and capabilitie=\r\ns) of the sadhaka. Only antaryaga and bahiryaga are relevant to our discuss=\r\nion. I have already expanded on this in another post on Yajna. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;5. D=\r\nevata Bheda: Though the Devi is only One, depending on the samskara and vas=\r\nana of the initiate, he is initiated into the worship of Kali or Sri and th=\r\nus the paths of Kalikula and Srikula or Kalividya and Srividya. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;6. =\r\nAchara Bheda: Depending on the initiate&#39;s samskara and adhikara, broadly sp=\r\neaking there are seven acharas- Vedachara,\n Vaisnavachara, Saivachara, Daks=\r\nhinachara, Vamachara, Siddhantachara , and Kaulachara. Within the framework=\r\n of Sakta sadhana, there are only three acharas- Samaya, Dakshina and Kaula=\r\nchara. It is highly misleading to speak of the *superiority* of one achara =\r\nover the other. The path, the chosen form of the Mother (Kali or Sri), the =\r\nmeans of worship, are all differently devised to suit the varying temperame=\r\nnts of the practitioners. All forms of the Devi and all paths of sadhana ar=\r\ne equally respectable and ancient enough. The differences pertain more to t=\r\nhe practitioner and NOT TO THE DIVINITY. As such we are advised not to degr=\r\nade or criticize any path or deity. All upasanas lead to the Devi and all s=\r\nadhakas have the Devi within them. To talk lowly of any other sadhana marga=\r\n or rupa of the Devi amounts to insulting the Devi Herself. As Sri Bhaskara=\r\nraya observes with characteristic tolerance, &quot;all vidyas are not different,=\r\n a comparison of one to another (in\n the texts) is merely for the sake of p=\r\nraising and encouraging its performance&quot;. One could as well extend this tol=\r\nerance (if not acceptance) to all forms of God and all paths of attaining H=\r\ner/Him. In the ultimate reckoning, any division is relative as there is onl=\r\ny the ONE. Advaita is the true essence of Sakta sadhana. All paths are prac=\r\ntically along a *circular* continuum. An intellectual debate on the differe=\r\nnces between various paths is irrelevant to sadhana itself though it has re=\r\nlevance to academicians or to the respective world-view of the sadhaka. Ins=\r\ntead sadhakas should focus on the underlying unity of all paths and the ult=\r\nimate Oneness of all forms of the Divine. This is a major tenet of Sakta sa=\r\ndhana.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;7. Mantra Bheda =E2=80=93 Based on certain factors including =\r\nthe sadhaka&#39;s adhikara bheda, he is initiated into a different mantra. It i=\r\ns not uncommon that the same sadhaka is initiated into various forms of the=\r\n mantra progressively in a gradual\n manner if he persists with commitment. =\r\nFor instance in Sri Vidya upasana the mantra of Sri has five variant versio=\r\nns- Bala, Panchadashi, Shodashi, Para shodashi and Guhya shodashi. Bala man=\r\ntra is the entry level or preparatory level mantra for Sri Vidya. Likewise =\r\nthe navakshari or navarna mantra too has SEVEN VARIANT versions, of which t=\r\nhe Navarna mantra that most written texts include is the mildest and akin t=\r\no the entry level Bala mantra in Sri Vidya upasana. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;The *details* o=\r\nf the seven variant versions of the navakshari or the twelve different ways=\r\n of doing Sri Sri Chandi path are really unnecessary to our current discuss=\r\nion. Instead in my next post I will write more on MANTRA and its central im=\r\nportance in sadhana as per the Sakta world-view. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Finally a word on =\r\n`Vak and `artha&#39; too is in order here. It is true that one derives great be=\r\nnefit by chanting a mantra in its original form. No doubt translation of a =\r\nmantra is NOT the same as\n the mantra in its original form as `vak&#39;. Undoub=\r\ntedly `Sabda&#39; comes first and then only the `artha&#39; follows (&quot;Artha Srishta=\r\neh Purvam Sabda srushtih&quot;). However one has to bear in mind that `Vak&#39; and =\r\n`Artha&#39; are interdependent and inseparable. I will elaborate on Sabda/Vak/A=\r\nrtha in my next post along with Sri Bhaskararaya makhin&#39;s commentary and th=\r\ne importance accorded to the fifteen levels of meaning (artha) of a mantra,=\r\n so much so that he even affirms that, &quot;the mere utterance of sabda without=\r\n a knowledge of the true import bears no fruit, even as the offering thrown=\r\n over ashes in the absence of fire does not burst into flame&quot;. I will exami=\r\nne both sides of `sabda&#39; and `artha&#39; in my next post as and when I can. All=\r\n Indian traditions that explore `Vak&#39; or `Sabda&#39; agree that both are insepa=\r\nrable. The very mention of the words `sabda&#39; and `artha&#39; brings to my mind =\r\nthe most beautiful mangala sloka from Kalidasa&#39;s `Raghuvamsa&#39; wherein he co=\r\nmpares the\n inseparable and interdependent nature of `Vak&#39; and `Artha&#39; to `=\r\nSiva&#39; and `Sakti&#39; the parents of the entire universe =E2=80=A6.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;vaga=\r\nrthaviva samprkthau vagarthaaprathipaththaye / &lt;BR&gt;jagathaha pitharau vandh=\r\ne parvathiparameshvarau // &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Regards,&lt;BR&gt;Satya Prakash&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;--- In =\r\n&lt;A href=3D&quot;mailto:vedic-wisdom%40yahoogroups.com&quot; target=3D_blank rel=3Dnof=\r\nollow ymailto=3D&quot;mailto:vedic-wisdom%40yahoogroups.com&quot;&gt;vedic-wisdom@yahoog=\r\nroups.com&lt;/A&gt;, rajarshi nandy &lt;rajarshi14@...&gt; wrote:&lt;BR&gt;&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&gt;=\r\n Dear Satya Prakash ji,&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Thank you for your beautiful=C3=82=\r\n&nbsp;analysis of Sri Sri Chandi. I read it and reflected &lt;BR&gt;&gt; on it, a=\r\nnd in my limited understand I agree to most of what you have said. &lt;BR&gt;&gt;=\r\n Specially your explanation pertaining to=C3=82&nbsp;Chand-munda and=C3=82&=\r\nnbsp;Sumbha-Nishumbh were &lt;BR&gt;&gt; awesome!&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; I have a quest=\r\nion about your following paragraph:&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;&lt;there are thos=\r\ne who adhere to the Tantric\n approach and do the sadhana as per &lt;BR&gt;&gt; th=\r\ne mantra marga. It is this particular approach that needs initiation as per=\r\n &lt;BR&gt;&gt; its own principles. Initiation is not mandatory if one adopts the=\r\n Vedantic path &lt;BR&gt;&gt; of Viveka and Vichara, or the Yogic path of Abhyasa=\r\n and Vairagya, or even the &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Pauranic approach of reading the text d=\r\nevoutly as Sacred Myth. Likewise Homam &lt;BR&gt;&gt; too is not required if one =\r\nis not inclined to the predominantly Vaidik practice &lt;BR&gt;&gt; of Ritual/Yag=\r\nnya. One may benefit from